EN Tandem van de Graaff accelerator

delta-E - E gas ionisation chamber. The
ionisation detector was coupled to the lid of a
small scattering chamber (~20 cm diameter) which was
tilted with respect to the base of the chamber.
A monitor detector placed at 45. degr.(lab. sys) was
used at all incident  energies to normalise between
runs on the Rutherford elastic scattering from
vanadium.
Absolute cross sections accurate to +-10%
were  obtained by normalising the 160 + 160 elastic
scattering to the Mott cross section at forward
scattering angles for a low beam energy.
EN Tandem van de Graaff accelerator
of the University of the Witwatersrand.
The 16-O target was prepared by evaporating V2O5
onto a previously mounted carbon foil of area
density 10 mu-g/cm2. During deposition the thickness
of the V2O5 was monitored continuously and was
determined more accurately subsequently by
Rutherford backscattering and energy-loss
measurements. Targets of 37+-3 mu-g/cm2 and
15+-2mu-g/cm2 were used (corresponding to an energy
loss of ~200keV and ~100keV, respectively, for E-lab
= 30 MeV 16-O ions).The thicker targets were used
for excitation functions in steps of delta-E-c.m.=
100keV and the thinner ones for steps of 50 keV.
Beam currents at the target were typically 45
particle nA.
